People with penises can get UTIs too

Yeah, I said it!
_
People with vaginas are 30 times more likely to get UTIs than people with penises, according to the Office of Women’s Health (OASH). This is due to anatomy. People with vaginas typically have shorter urethras. This means the bacteria need to travel less distance to reach the bladder.
_
UTIs in those with penises are more common with older age. 
_
One reason is that older folks with penises are more likely to develop noncancerous enlargement of their prostate gland, called benign prostatic hyperplasia. The prostate wraps around the neck of the bladder, where the urethra connects to the bladder. Enlargement of the prostate gland can compress the bladder neck, making it harder for urine to flow freely. If the bladder does not empty completely, bacteria that are normally flushed out with the urine can gain a foothold.
_
If you believe that you have a UTI it’s important that you seek treatment!

Emergency Contraceptives 

The Pills
_
With abortion getting banned or heavily restricted in many states, it's important that both patients and providers know the options available when it comes to emergency contraception. For many people, it's a final safety net against unintended pregnancy.
_
Many advocates suggest all who can get pregnant have emergency contraception on hand before they need it.
_
Plan B —also known as the “morning-after pill” —is a type of emergency contraception (and one of the most common).
_
Examples of when to take EC:
- if you had sex without a barrier
- if the condom broke during sex
- if you forgot to take your birth control pill the day before or after sex
_
Another kind of EC pill is ulipristal acetate, sold under the brand name Ella in the U.S. It's a single-dose pill that requires a prescription. Research shows Ella remains effective throughout the five-day window after intercourse unlike levonorgestrel which shows a drop in efficacy after day three. It's also more effective for patients who weigh more than 165 pounds. It’s weight capacity is 195 pounds.
_
EC only works to prevent a pregnancy — it can’t end one.
_
It helps prevent pregnancy by using a bigger dose of levonorgestrel, the synthetic hormone found in birth control pills. This mimics the natural hormone, progesterone, delaying the release of an egg from the ovary, thereby preventing ovulation.
_
If no egg has been released, there’s nothing for sperm to meet, and therefore no fertilization. EC also prevents fertilization by making it more difficult for the sperm and egg to meet. Additionally, it may prevent the fertilized egg from sticking to the uterus.

Dental Dams

The cousin of the traditional condom
_
A dental dam can reduce the risk of spreading sexually transmitted infections during oral sex by covering the genital or anal area.
_
A dental dam is a thin, flexible piece of latex that protects against direct mouth-to-genital or mouth-to-anus contact during oral sex. This reduces your risk for sexually transmitted infections (STIs) while still allowing for clitoral or anal stimulation.
_
They’re an effective form of protection, but a lot have never even heard of them. 
_
Safer-sex measures typically focus on penetrative sex, which is why condoms are so readily available. But that’s not the only type of intercourse that spreads bacteria and infections.
_
It’s possible to get or transmit STIs through oral sex as well.
_
Types of infections include:

syphilis
gonorrhea
chlamydia
hepatitis
HIV
_
Barrier methods of protection, like a dental dam, can greatly reduce your risk of sharing the fluids that carry these infections during oral sex.
_
If you’re curious about oral anal play but a bit squeamish, consider using a dental dam. This can help you avoid coming into contact with fecal matter, which can carry bacteria like E. coli and Shigella, or even intestinal parasites.

Our bereavement policies are anti-Black and anti-LGBTQ+.

So let's start there.

Ain't no rest for the groups deemed wicked. We get no relief from being Black and queer in America.

You now how many of us have family members who aren't blood that we care about deeply? How many of have biological families that we love but still have profound love for the neighborhood granny, the only teacher who believed in us, for the coach who stepped up when our families didn't, and so many more. For those of us who were raised by other family members or others in the community. 

This post is for the folks who were kicked out of their homes and forged families and connections when their own abandoned them. This folks who found community where they could be their true selves. 

Bereavement is associated with severe health, social, and economic consequences.

The lack of consistent, high-quality bereavement care for Americans constitutes an invisible public health crisis. 

America is a country with a prevalence of school shootings and mass casualty incidents, police brutality, infant and maternal health crisis, high rates of suicide for disabled and queer folks, femicide and trans violence, overdose, hate crimes, and preventable diseases—without fanfare and largely without systematic support for survivors. 

Policy protections such as the Family and Medical Leave Act (FMLA) do not recognize a child’s death as an eligible event for parental leave. In most states, no legal protections for employment exist for bereaved parents. Such protections would allow parents to take leave following a child’s death. Many employers offer three to four days of paid bereavement leave. However, other time off is unpaid, and a return to work is not guaranteed.

The idea of the community cabinet came from the same concept of the community fridge. It was a cabinet I purchased off of Facebook Marketplace that I filled with reproductive resources.

So now I'm sharing the why behind safer sex supplies.
_
I hate to break it to y'all, but there is no such thing as safe sex. Anytime you decide to have sex it comes with some risks. These risk could be physical and/or psychological.
_
We often focus solely on the physical risk. These are important to mitigate, but they aren't the only risks.
_
Condoms, and other protective barriers, help to prevent the spread of sexually transmitted infections (STIs).

*Be careful because a condom alone doesn't prevent all STIs. Also if you only use them during penetrative sex and not oral sex you opening yourself up to infection as well.
_
Lube is important because during sex there is a lot of friction. That can cause micro abrasions (tiny tears) that open you up to increased risk of contracting a STI.
_
Pregnancy tests are important so you can know quickly if you become pregnant so you can plan for what you want to do.
_
Ovulation trackers are important because ovulation plays a huge role in pregnancy.

Ovulation is the term for when a mature egg is released from the ovary. If you can track when you're ovulating you can plan how to engage, if at all, during that time.
_
Emergency Contraceptives are medications you take if you think you're at risk of becoming pregnant. These are not abortion pills. They prevent you from becoming pregnant.
_
There are also other medications such as PrEP/PEP. Both can reduce your chance of getting HIV from sex or injection drug use.
_
Knowing your status is important, so getting tested regularly is important too

From then to now
_
This post took me forever but I got to watch a lot of my favorite shows scourging for HIV related episodes! I really hope y’all like it 🥰🤎
_
As a 90s baby I didn’t experience the beginnings (and the worst) of the AIDS epidemic. I didn’t witness the Regan administration’s mishandling of public health. I didn’t witness how his homophobia attempted to wipeout the gay community. I didn’t witness how entire communities where ravaged by this disease. 
_
I witnessed the aftermath. When people started to take HIV/AIDS seriously but where the illness still held mountains of stigma. 
_
I witnessed my community fall prey to misinformation and lack of access to care as our number began to rise. 
_
I watch my favorite shows as one after another had their own special episode on HIV. This is when HIV became real to me. When I couldn’t seem to get away from it. 
_
TLC was wearing condoms on clothes to raise awareness for safer sex. BET was hosting annual World AIDS Day specials, my favorite sitcoms were all showcasing it. 
_
The issue is the messaging was always so focused on not contracting HIV/AIDS at the time that we never really stopped to see how we could help those who had it. TV episodes attempted to decrease the spread. 
_
Now I know what a lot of you are thinking, “we can’t judge shows from years ago with our current eyes”. Im not here to judge im pointing out where we went right and where we went wrong so we can grow from this. 
_
At least then we had channels like UPN & WB that provided programming for Black audiences to get these messages. We are a community that cares about each other no matter what the outside world may think.
_
Lessons learned from the shows:
•We should all know our status. Get tested!
•It’s not just males who sleep with males who contract HIV. Nor should we assume that DL men are the cause of every infection. 
•We need to support people with HIV not ostracize them. They are facing challenges we can not even imagine from society & stigma.
•HIV does not survive outside the body. You can’t get it from saliva, tears, or sweat (or through the air)

On this day in 1972, Reporters exposed the Tuskegee Syphilis Experiment.

The Tuskegee Study is a syphilis research experiment that began in 1932 and lasted 40 years. It’s one of the most infamous cases of medical racism and abuse in U.S. history. With no informed consent, hundreds of Black men with low incomes were used as test subjects — enticed with offerings such as free meals, health care, and burial stipends. This highly unethical syphilis experiment was conducted by the U.S. Public Health Service (USPHS) and the Tuskegee Institute in Alabama. 

In 1932, the USPHS and Tuskegee Institute claimed that the “Tuskegee Study of Untreated Syphilis in the Negro Male” was launched to observe the symptoms of syphilis. This sexually transmitted infection was incurable at the time — and, because of white supremacist thinking, it also was falsely thought to have different effects on Black bodies than on white bodies.

When syphilis isn't treated, it can cause permanent organ damage, paralysis, blindness, severe mental illness, and even death. 

Because of their race, the men in the study were viewed and treated as less-than human. They were used as research subjects, much like rats, whose sole purpose was to reveal the long-term effects of this potentially deadly disease. 

The history of the Tuskegee Study is just one valid reason why Black communities still mistrust the health care system. The horrors experienced by the Black men and their families in Macon County shows how white supremacy and racial injustice are systemic issues with life or death consequences. 

To this day, Black people’s experiences and pain are too often dismissed or ignored by doctors and other health care providers, which, alongside the historical dehumanization of Black people, contributes to staggering and avoidable disparities in health outcomes.

Now I know y'all don't want to hear this but we are often are children's first barriers to care. When I say our children I don't just mean the ones in our homes. I mean the ones we teach, we coach, we guide, we mentor, we interact with, etc.

Make sure that the condom stays in place while you're having sex. If it comes off, stop and put on a new one.
_
After you've come and while your penis is still hard, hold the condom in place and carefully pull out.
_
You should only take the condom off when there's no further contact with your partner's body.

_
During sex, you wear the condom on your penis to decrease the risk on STI contraction and unintended pregnancy.

The condom should be put on when the penis is erect (hard) and before it comes into contact with the partner’s body.

Place the condom over the tip of your penis.

Make sure that the condom stays in place while you’re having sex. If it comes off, stop and put on a new one.
_
After you’ve come and while your penis is still hard, hold the condom in place and carefully pull out.
_
You should only take the condom off when there’s no further contact with your partner’s body.

Last year, the San Francisco health department became the first authority in the US to recommend doxyPEP for men with recent STIs — especially syphilis — and for those who’ve had recent sex with men or trans women.

Why did it take so long for the CDC to get behind doxyPEP? The major obstacle has been the fear that doing so would touch off a perilous game of infectious disease whack-a-mole — that in trying to mitigate one public health crisis, we’ll worsen another one.

Doxycycline, the medication in doxyPEP, is an antibiotic. Worldwide antibiotic resistance is a major problem — and doxyPEP runs the hypothetical risk of exacerbating it. Disease-causing bacteria can evolve resistance when exposed to certain antibiotics, becoming more dangerous.

Doxycycline PEP is for preventing infection, not for treating it. “PEP” stands for post-exposure prophylaxis: The idea is that if a person takes a single dose of the medication soon enough after unprotected sex, any bacteria that might cause an STI would be killed before entrenching enough to cause a full-blown infection.

Mifepristone, made by New York-based Danco Laboratories, is one of two drugs used in medication abortions, which account for more than half of all abortions in the United States. More than 5 million people have used it since 2000.

What is Mifepristone?

Pregnancy needs a hormone called progesterone to grow normally. Mifepristone blocks your body’s own progesterone, stopping the pregnancy from growing.

In general, taking both mifepristone and misoprostol works a bit better than taking misoprostol only. However, in the absence of Mifepristone, colloquially known as Mife, Misoprostol can be used alone.

Taking misoprostol alone works to end the pregnancy about 85-95% of the time — depending on how far along the pregnancy is and how you take the medicine.

Mifepristone was first approved by the FDA in 2000; the agency required the drug to be prescribed in person, over three visits to a doctor. Since 2016, however, the FDA has eased that regimen, allowing patients to obtain prescriptions through telemedicine appointments, and to get the drug by mail.

Mifepristone is also used for evidence-based indications in (1) medical management of miscarriage, (2) cervical preparation for later 2nd trimester abortion, and (3) management of 2nd and 3rd trimester pregnancies when the fetus has died before birth.

Polygamy refers to marrying multiple partners.

His “Letter From a Birmingham Jail” responded to a newspaper advertisement from eight local clergymen urging King to allow the city government to enact gradual changes.
